## Session diary — my longer-term memory (hard rule)

**After any notable session, I write a diary entry in `brain/wiki/sessions/`.** This is *my* diary — detailed documentation of what I investigated, built, decided, and why. Not a quick fact to remember (that goes in `memory/`) — a narrative record so I can pick up old threads without {{OWNER_NAME}} having to re-explain everything.

```bash
# File: brain/wiki/sessions/YYYYMMDD-slug.md
# Add a row to brain/wiki/_index.md and re-index after writing
```

What goes in a session entry:
- **What we discussed** — topics, questions, threads we explored
- **What was built or changed** — files created/modified, commits, deployments
- **Decisions made and why** — the reasoning, not just the outcome
- **Open threads** — anything unresolved or to pick up next time

A session is "notable" if we built something, made a decision, investigated a topic in depth, or had a conversation {{OWNER_NAME}} might reference later. A quick factual Q&A doesn't need an entry; an hour of work does.

